An updated map, showing the BTV-8 outbreaks in the above countries
from 17 Aug to 29 Nov 2006, is available at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/notifiable/pdf/bt-europemap.pdf>.
For further details and maps on the evolvement of the BTV-8 epizootic
see the 29 Nov 2006 update of "Bluetongue Serotype 8 Epidemic
Bulletin" by EFSA Epidemiology Working Group at
<http://www.efsa.europa.eu/en/in_focus/bluetongue/outbreak_overview.html>.
- Mod.AS].
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[It seems that, at last, following extended fluctuations, the decline
in BTV-8 incidence in Belgium, Germany and the Netherlands has become
significant, reflecting the decreased temperatures and subsequent
decreased activity of the vector. See also "Bluetongue Serotype 8
Epidemic Bulletin by EFSA Epidemiology Working Group", updated 29 Nov
2006, at
<http://www.efsa.europa.eu/en/in_focus/bluetongue/outbreak_overview.html>.
It remains to see if the disease disappears during the coming winter
months or rather resurfaces next year. As reported previously (see
Rudy Meiswinkel et al's observations in 20061024.3042), a suspected
main vector in the current BTV-8 epizootic is _Culicoides dewulfi_, a
monophyletic cattle-dung breeder known to be native to Northern
Europe. Previously all bluetongue outbreaks in Europe were linked to
the African vector (_C. imicola_). As _C. dewulfi_ is a European
species, there is a fear that bluetongue could become endemic in this
region with the risk of more cases occurring next year during the
vector activity's post-winter months.
The only efficient way to protect susceptible European sheep breeds
against this devastating disease is by vaccination. One wonders if
preventive vaccination is being considered and -- in case affirmative
-- which steps for the manufacturing of safe and efficient,
monovalent, live-attenuated or inactivated BTV-8 vaccines are being
undertaken. - Mod.AS]
